# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-liberation-press-office
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] An **acronym** is an abbreviation formed using the initial letters of a multi-word name or phrase.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often spelled with the initial letter of each word in all caps with no punctuation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In English, the word is used in two ways.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In the narrow sense, an acronym is a sequence of letters (representing the initial letters of words in a phrase) when pronounced together as a single word, like *NASA*, *NATO*, or *laser*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In the broad sense, the term includes this kind of sequence when pronounced letter by letter (such as *GDP* or *USA*).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Sources that differentiate the two often call the former acronyms and the latter **initialisms** or **alphabetisms**.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] However, *acronym* is popularly used to refer to either concept, and both senses of the term are attributed as far back as the 1940s.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Dictionary and style-guide editors dispute whether the term *acronym* can be legitimately applied to abbreviations which are not pronounced as words, and there is no general agreement on standard acronym spacing, casing, and punctuation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The phrase that the acronym stands for is called its *expansion*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The *meaning* of an acronym includes both its expansion and the meaning of its expansion.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The word *acronym* is formed from the Greek roots *akro-*, meaning 'height, summit, or tip', and *-nym*, 'name'.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] This neoclassical compound appears to have originated in German, with attestations for the German form *Akronym* appearing as early as 1921.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Citations in English date to a 1940 translation of a novel by the German writer Lion Feuchtwanger.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] English lexicography and style guides differ on whether *acronym* should apply only to abbreviations pronounced as ordinary words or also to letter-by-letter initialisms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some authorities accept or record the broader sense; others restrict *acronym* to word-pronounced forms and prefer *initialism* (or simply *abbreviation*) for the rest.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Among sources that acknowledge the broader sense, attitudes range from neutral recording to prescriptive criticism.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some mainstream English dictionaries from across the English-speaking world affirm a sense of *acronym* that does not require its pronunciation as a word.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] English language usage and style guides which have entries for *acronym* generally criticize the usage that refers to forms that are not pronounceable words.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In contrast, some style guides do support it, whether explicitly or implicitly.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The 1994 edition of *Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage* defends the usage on the basis of a claim that dictionaries do not make a distinction.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The BuzzFeed style guide describes CBS and PBS as "acronyms ending in S".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Most of the dictionary entries and style guide recommendations regarding the term *acronym* in the twentieth century did not explicitly acknowledge or support the expansive sense.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The Merriam–Webster's Dictionary of English Usage from 1994 is one of the earliest publications to advocate for the expansive sense, and all the major dictionary editions that include a sense of *acronym* equating it with *initialism* were first published in the twenty-first century.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* only included the exclusive sense for *acronym* and its earliest citation was from 1943.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In early December 2010, Duke University researcher Stephen Goranson published a citation for *acronym* to the American Dialect Society e-mail discussion list which refers to *PGN* being pronounced "pee-gee-enn", antedating English language usage of the word to 1940.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Linguist Ben Zimmer then mentioned this citation in his December 16, 2010 "On Language" column about acronyms in *The New York Times Magazine*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] By 2011, the publication of the 3rd edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* added the expansive sense to its entry for *acronym* and included the 1940 citation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] As the *Oxford English Dictionary* structures the senses in order of chronological development, it now gives the "initialism" sense first.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Acronymy, like retronymy, is a linguistic process that has existed throughout history but for which there was little to no naming, conscious attention, or systematic analysis until relatively recent times.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Like retronymy, it became much more common in the twentieth century than it had formerly been.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] American Telephone and Telegraph Company → AT&T).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some well-known commercial examples dating from the 1890s through 1920s include "Nabisco" ("National Biscuit Company"), "Esso" (from "S.O.", from "Standard Oil"), and "Sunoco" ("Sun Oil Company").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Another field for the adoption of acronyms was modern warfare, with its many highly technical terms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The widespread, frequent use of acronyms across the whole range of linguistic registers is relatively new in most languages, becoming increasingly evident since the mid-twentieth century.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] As literacy spread and technology produced a constant stream of new and complex terms, abbreviations became increasingly convenient.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (*OED*) records the first printed use of the word *initialism* as occurring in 1899, but it did not come into general use until 1965, well after *acronym* had become common.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In English, acronyms *pronounced as words* may be a twentieth-century phenomenon.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Linguist David Wilton in *Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends* claims that "forming words from acronyms is a distinctly twentieth- (and now twenty-first-) century phenomenon.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] There is only one known pre-twentieth-century [English] word with an acronymic origin and it was in vogue for only a short time in 1886.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The use of Latin and Neo-Latin terms in vernaculars has been pan-European and pre-dates modern English.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The earliest example of a word derived from an acronym listed by the *OED* is "abjud" (now "abjad"), formed from the original first four letters of the Arabic alphabet in the late eighteenth century.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some acrostics pre-date this, however, such as the Restoration witticism arranging the names of some members of Charles II's Committee for Foreign Affairs to produce the "CABAL" ministry.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Acronyms are used most often to abbreviate names of organizations and long or frequently referenced terms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The armed forces and government agencies frequently employ acronyms; some well-known examples from the United States are among the "alphabet agencies" (jokingly referred to as "alphabet soup") created under the New Deal by Franklin D.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Business and industry also coin acronyms prolifically.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The rapid advance of science and technology also drives the usage, as new inventions and concepts with multiword names create a demand for shorter, more pronounceable names.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] One representative example, from the U.S.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Navy, is "COMCRUDESPAC", which stands for "commander, cruisers destroyers Pacific"; it is also seen as "ComCruDesPac".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Acronym use has been further popularized by text messaging on mobile phones with short message service (SMS), and instant messenger (IM).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] To fit messages into the 160-character SMS limit, and to save time, acronyms such as "GF" ("girlfriend"), "LOL" ("laughing out loud"), and "DL" ("download" or "down low") have become popular.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some prescriptivists disdain texting acronyms and abbreviations as decreasing clarity, or as failure to use "pure" or "proper" English.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Others point out that languages have always continually changed, and argue that acronyms should be embraced as inevitable, or as innovation that adapts the language to changing circumstances.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In this view, the modern practice is just the "proper" English of the current generation of speakers, much like the earlier abbreviation of corporation names on ticker tape or newspapers.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Exact pronunciation of "word acronyms" (those pronounced as words rather than sounded out as individual letters) often vary by speaker population.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] These may be regional, occupational, or generational differences, or simply personal preference.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For instance, there have been decades of online debate about how to pronounce GIF (/ɡɪf/ or /dʒɪf/) and BIOS (/ˈbaɪoʊs/, /ˈbaɪoʊz/, or /ˈbaɪɒs/).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Pronunciation may even vary within a single speaker's vocabulary, depending on narrow contexts.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] As an example, the database programming language SQL is usually said as three letters, but in reference to Microsoft's implementation is traditionally pronounced like the word *sequel*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In writing for a broad audience, the words of an acronym are typically written out in full at its first occurrence within a given text.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use (EAFU) benefits readers unfamiliar with the acronym.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Another text aid is an abbreviation key which lists and expands all acronyms used, a reference for readers who skipped past the first use.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] (This is especially important for paper media, where no search utility is available to find the first use.) It also gives students a convenient review list to memorize the important acronyms introduced in a textbook chapter.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use and abbreviation keys originated in the print era, but they are equally useful for electronic text.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] While acronyms provide convenience and succinctness for specialists, they often degenerate into confusing jargon.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] This may be intentional, to exclude readers without domain-specific knowledge.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] New acronyms may also confuse when they coincide with an already existing acronym having a different meaning.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Medical literature has been struggling to control the proliferation of acronyms, including efforts by the American Academy of Dermatology.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often taught as mnemonic devices: for example the colors of the rainbow are ROY G.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] BIV (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] They are also used as mental checklists: in aviation GUMPS stands for gas-undercarriage-mixture-propeller-seat belts.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Other mnemonic acronyms include HOMES (for the North American Great Lakes) in geography, PAVPANIC in English grammar, and PEMDAS/BODMAS in mathematics.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] It is not uncommon for acronyms to be cited in a kind of false etymology, called a folk etymology, for a word.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Such etymologies persist in popular culture but have no factual basis in historical linguistics, and are examples of language-related urban legends.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, "cop" is commonly cited as being derived, it is presumed, from "constable on patrol", and "posh" from "port outward, starboard home".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] With some of these specious expansions, the "belief" that the etymology is acronymic has clearly been tongue-in-cheek among many citers, as with "gentlemen only, ladies forbidden" for "golf", although many other (more credulous) people have uncritically taken it for fact.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Taboo words in particular commonly have such false etymologies: "shit" from "ship/store high in transit" or "special high-intensity training" and "fuck" from "for unlawful carnal knowledge", or "fornication under consent/command of the king".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In English, abbreviations have previously been marked by a wide variety of punctuation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Obsolete forms include using an overbar or colon to show the ellipsis of letters following the initial part.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The forward slash is still common in many dialects for some fixed expressions—such as in *w/* for "with" or *A/C* for "air conditioning"—while only infrequently being used to abbreviate new terms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The apostrophe is common for grammatical contractions (e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] *don't*, *y'all*, and *ain't*) and for contractions marking unusual pronunciations (e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] *a'ight*, *cap'n*, and *fo'c'sle* for "all right", "captain", and "forecastle").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] By the early twentieth century, it was standard to use a full stop/period/point, especially in the cases of initialisms and acronyms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Previously, especially for Latin abbreviations, this was done with a full space between every full word (e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] This even included punctuation after both Roman and Arabic numerals to indicate their use in place of the full names of each number (e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Both conventions have fallen out of common use in all dialects of English, except in places where an Arabic decimal includes a medial decimal point.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Particularly in British and Commonwealth English, all such punctuation marking acronyms and other capitalized abbreviations is now uncommon and considered either unnecessary or incorrect.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The presence of all-capital letters is now thought sufficient to indicate the nature of the *UK*, the *EU*, and the *UN*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Forms such as *the U.S.A.* for "the United States of America" are now considered to indicate American or North American English.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Even within those dialects, such punctuation is becoming increasingly uncommon.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some style guides, such as that of the BBC, no longer require punctuation to show ellipsis; some even proscribe it.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Nevertheless, some influential style guides, many of them American, still require periods in certain instances.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* recommends following each segment with a period when the letters are pronounced individually, as in "K.G.B.", but not when pronounced as a word, as in "NATO".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the punctuation scheme.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] When a multiple-letter abbreviation is formed from a single word, periods are in general not used, although they may be common in informal usage.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] "TV", for example, may stand for a *single* word ("television", for instance), and is in general spelled without punctuation (except in the plural).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Although "PS" stands for the single English word "postscript" or the Latin *postscriptum*, it is often spelled with periods ("P.S.") as if parsed as Latin *post scriptum* instead.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The slash ('/', or *solidus*) is sometimes used to separate the letters in an acronym, as in "N/A" ("not applicable, not available") and "c/o" ("care of").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Inconveniently long words used frequently in related contexts can be represented according to their letter count as a numeronym.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, "i18n" abbreviates "internationalization", a computer-science term for adapting software for worldwide use; the "18" represents the 18 letters that come between the first and the last in "internationalization".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Similarly, "localization" can be abbreviated "l10n"; "multilingualization" "m17n"; and "accessibility" "a11y".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In addition to the use of a specific number replacing that many letters, the more general "x" can be used to replace an unspecified number of letters.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Examples include "Crxn" for "crystallization" and the series familiar to physicians for history, diagnosis, and treatment ("hx", "dx", "tx").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Terms relating to a command structure may also sometimes use this formatting, for example gold, silver, and bronze levels of command in UK policing being referred to as Gx, Sx, and Bx.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] There is a question about how to pluralize acronyms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Often a writer will add an 's' following an apostrophe, as in "PC's".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Turabian's *A Manual for Writers of Research Papers, Theses, and Dissertations*, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Turabian would therefore prefer "DVDs" and "URLs" but not "Ph.D.s".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Possessive plurals that also include apostrophes for mere pluralization and periods appear especially complex: for example, "the C.D.'s' labels" (the labels of the compact discs).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In some instances, however, an apostrophe may increase clarity: for example, if the final letter of an abbreviation is "S", as in "SOS's" (although abbreviations ending with S can also take "-es", e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] "SOSes"), or when pluralizing an abbreviation that has periods.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] A particularly rich source of options arises when the plural of an acronym would normally be indicated in a word other than the final word if spelled out in full.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] A classic example is "Member of Parliament", which in plural is "Members of Parliament".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] It is possible then to abbreviate this as "M's P", which was fairly common in mid-twentieth-century Australian news writing (or similar), and used by former Australian Prime Minister Ben Chifley.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] This usage is less common than forms with "s" at the end, such as "MPs", and may appear dated or pedantic.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In common usage, therefore, "weapons of mass destruction" becomes "WMDs", "prisoners of war" becomes "POWs", and "runs batted in" becomes "RBIs".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Abbreviations that come from single, rather than multiple, words—such as "TV" ("television")—are usually pluralized without apostrophes ("two TVs"); most writers feel that the apostrophe should be reserved for the possessive ("the TV's antenna").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In some languages, the convention of doubling the letters in the acronym is used to indicate plural words: for example, the Spanish *EE.UU.*, for *Estados Unidos* ('United States').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] This old convention is still sometimes followed for a limited number of English abbreviations, such as *SS.* for *Saints*, *pp.* for the plural of 'pages', or *mss.* for *manuscripts*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The most common capitalization scheme seen with acronyms is all-uppercase (all caps).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Small caps are sometimes used to make the run of capital letters seem less jarring to the reader.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, the style of some American publications, including the *Atlantic Monthly* and *USA Today*, is to use small caps for acronyms longer than three letters; thus "U.S." and "FDR" are set in normal caps, but "nato" is set in small caps.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The acronyms "AD" and "BC" are often smallcapped as well, as in: "From 4004 bc to ad 525".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Where an acronym has linguistically taken on an identity as regular word, the acronym may use normal case rules, e.g. it would appear generally in lower case, but with an initial capital when starting a sentence or when in a title.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Once knowledge of the words underlying such an acronym has faded from common recall, the acronym may be termed an **anacronym**.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Examples of anacronyms are the words "scuba", "radar", and "laser".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The word "an*acro*nym" should not be confused with the word "an*achro*nym", which is a type of misnomer.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Words derived from an acronym by affixing are typically expressed in mixed case, so the root acronym is clear.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, "pre-WWII politics", "post-NATO world", "DNase".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] In some cases a derived acronym may also be expressed in mixed case.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, "messenger RNA" and "transfer RNA" become "mRNA" and "tRNA".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some publications choose to capitalize only the first letter of acronyms, reserving all-caps styling for initialisms, writing the pronounced acronyms "Nato" and "Aids" in mixed case, but the initialisms "USA" and "FBI" in all caps.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, this is the style used in *The Guardian*, and *BBC News* typically edits to this style (though its official style guide, dating from 2003, still recommends all-caps).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the capitalization scheme.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] However, it conflicts with conventional English usage of first-letter upper-casing as a marker of proper names in many cases.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] For example, *AIDS* stands for *acquired immunodeficiency syndrome*, which is not a proper name, while *Aids* is in the style of one.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Some style manuals also base the letters' case on their number.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] While abbreviations typically exclude the initials of short function words (such as "and", "or", "of", or "to"), this is not always the case.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Sometimes function words are included to make a pronounceable acronym, such as CORE (Congress of Racial Equality).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Sometimes the letters representing these words are written in lower case, such as in the cases of "TfL" ("Transport for London") and *LotR* (*The Lord of the Rings*); this usually occurs when the acronym represents a multi-word proper noun.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Numbers (both cardinal and ordinal) in names are often represented by digits rather than initial letters, as in "4GL" ("fourth generation language") or "G77" ("Group of 77").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Large numbers may use metric prefixes, as with "Y2K" for "Year 2000".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Exceptions using initials for numbers include "TLA" ("three-letter acronym/abbreviation") and "GoF" ("Gang of Four").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Authors of expository writing will sometimes capitalize or otherwise distinctively format the initials of the expansion for pedagogical emphasis (for example, writing: "the onset of Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)" or "the onset of **c**ongestive **h**eart **f**ailure (CHF)").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p01] Capitalization like this, however, conflicts with the convention of English orthography, which generally reserves capitals in the middle of sentences for proper nouns; when following the AMA Manual of Style, this would instead be rendered as "the onset of congestive heart failure (CHF)".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some apparent acronyms or other abbreviations do not stand for anything and cannot be expanded to some meaning.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Such pseudo-acronyms may be pronunciation-based, such as "BBQ" (*bee-bee-cue*), for "barbecue", and "K9" (*kay-nine*) for "canine".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms also frequently develop as "orphan initialisms": an existing acronym is redefined as a non-acronymous name, severing its link to its previous meaning.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For example, the letters of the "SAT", a US college entrance test originally dubbed "Scholastic Aptitude Test", no longer officially stand for anything.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] This is common with companies that want to retain brand recognition while moving away from an outdated image: American Telephone and Telegraph became AT&T and British Petroleum became BP.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] *Russia Today* has rebranded itself as *RT*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] American Movie Classics has simply rebranded itself as AMC.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Genzyme Transgenics Corporation became GTC Biotherapeutics, Inc.; The Learning Channel became TLC; MTV dropped the name Music Television out of its brand; and American District Telegraph became simply known as ADT.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] "Kentucky Fried Chicken" went partway, re-branding itself with its initialism "KFC" to de-emphasize the role of frying in the preparation of its signature dishes, though they have since returned to using both interchangeably.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The East Coast Hockey League became the ECHL when it expanded to include cities in the western United States prior to the 2003–2004 season.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms may have advantages in international markets: for example, some national affiliates of International Business Machines are legally incorporated with "IBM" in their names (for example, IBM Canada) to avoid translating the full name into local languages.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Likewise, UBS is the name of the merged Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corporation, and HSBC has replaced the long name Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The India-based JSW Group of companies is another example of the original name (Jindal South West Group) being re-branded into a pseudo-acronym while expanding into other geographical areas in and outside of India.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Rebranding can lead to redundant acronym syndrome, as when Trustee Savings Bank became TSB Bank, or when Railway Express Agency became REA Express.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] A few high-tech companies have taken the redundant acronym to the extreme: for example, ISM Information Systems Management Corp. and SHL Systemhouse Ltd.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Examples in entertainment include the television shows *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* and *Navy: NCIS* ("Navy" was dropped in the second season), where the redundancy was likely designed to educate new viewers as to what the initials stood for.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In some cases, while the initials in an acronym may stay the same, for what those letters stand may change.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] A *backronym* (or *bacronym*) is a phrase that is constructed "after the fact" from a previously existing word.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For example, the novelist and critic Anthony Burgess once proposed that the word "book" ought to stand for "box of organized knowledge".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] A classic real-world example of this is the name of the predecessor to the Apple Macintosh, the Apple Lisa, which was said to refer to "Local Integrated Software Architecture", but was actually named after Steve Jobs' daughter, born in 1978.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms are deliberately designed to be apt for the thing being named (by having a dual meaning or by borrowing the positive connotations of an existing word).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some examples of contrived acronyms are *USA PATRIOT*, *CAN SPAM*, *CAPTCHA*, *DOGE* and *ACT UP*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The clothing company French Connection began referring to itself as *fcuk*, standing for "French Connection United Kingdom".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The company then created T-shirts and several advertising campaigns that exploit the acronym's similarity to the taboo word "fuck".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms find frequent use as names of fictional agencies, with a famous example being frequent James Bond antagonist organization SPECTRE (Special Executive for Counterintelligence, Terrorism, Revenge and Extortion).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Department of Defense's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) is known for developing contrived acronyms to name projects, including *RESURRECT*, *NIRVANA*, and *DUDE*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The short-form names of clinical trials and other scientific studies constitute a large class of acronyms that includes many contrived examples, as well as many with a partial rather than complete correspondence of letters to expansion components.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Examples widely known in medicine include the ALLHAT trial (Antihypertensive and Lipid-Lowering Treatment to Prevent Heart Attack Trial) and the CHARM trial (Candesartan in Heart Failure: Assessment of Reduction in Mortality and Morbidity).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] However, the purpose of clinical trial acronyms, as with gene and protein symbols, is simply to have a syntactically usable and easily recalled short name to complement the long name that is often syntactically unusable and not memorized.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] It is useful for the short name to give a reminder of the long name, which supports the reasonable censure of "cutesy" examples that provide little to no hint of it.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] But beyond that reasonably close correspondence, the short name's chief utility is in functioning cognitively as a name, rather than being a cryptic and forgettable string, albeit faithful to the matching of letters.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] At least one study has evaluated the citation impact and other traits of acronym-named trials compared with others, finding both good aspects (mnemonic help, name recall) and potential flaws (connotatively driven bias).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are chosen deliberately to avoid a name considered undesirable: For example, *Verliebt in Berlin* (*ViB*), a German telenovela, was first intended to be *Alles nur aus Liebe* ('All for Love'), but was changed to avoid the resultant acronym *ANAL*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Computer Literacy and Internet Technology qualification is known as *CLaIT*, rather than *CLIT*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In Canada, the Canadian Conservative Reform Alliance (Party) was quickly renamed to the "Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance" when its opponents pointed out that its initials spelled CCRAP (pronounced "see crap").
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Two Irish institutes of technology (Galway and Tralee) chose different acronyms from other institutes when they were upgraded from regional technical colleges.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Tralee RTC became the Institute of Technology Tralee (ITT), as opposed to Tralee Institute of Technology (TIT).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Galway RTC became Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology (GMIT), as opposed to Galway Institute of Technology (GIT).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The charity sports organization Team in Training is known as "TNT" and not "TIT".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Technological Institute of Textile & Sciences, however, is still known as "TITS".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] George Mason University was planning to name their law school the "Antonin Scalia School of Law" (ASSOL) in honor of the late Antonin Scalia, only to change it to the "Antonin Scalia Law School" later.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] A **macronym**, or **nested acronym**, is an acronym in which one or more letters stand for acronyms (or abbreviations) themselves.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The word "macronym" is a portmanteau of "macro-" and "acronym".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some macronyms can be multiply nested: the second-order acronym points to another one further down a hierarchy.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] VITAL, for example, which expands to "VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries" is a total of 15 words when fully expanded.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Fully expanded, "RARS" might thus become "Regional Advanced Television Infrared Observational Satellite Operational Vertical Sounder Retransmission Service", which would produce the much more unwieldy acronym "RATIOSOVSRS".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The latter are fully reducible in an attempt to "spell everything out and avoid all abbreviations", but the former are irreducible in that respect; they can be annotated with parenthetical explanations, but they cannot be eliminated from speech or writing in any useful or practical way.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The name is thus itself more symbol than acronym, and its expansion cannot replace it while preserving its function in natural syntax as a name within a clause clearly parsable by human readers or listeners.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] A special type of macronym, the recursive acronym, has letters whose expansion refers back to the macronym itself.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] One of the earliest examples appears in *The Hacker's Dictionary* as MUNG, which stands for "MUNG Until No Good".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] With English terminology, discussions of languages with syllabic or logographic writing systems (such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean), "acronyms" describe the short forms that take selected characters from a multi-character word.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For example, in Chinese, 'university' (大學/大学, lit.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] 'great learning') is usually abbreviated simply as 大 ('great') when used with the name of the institute.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] So 'Peking University' (北京大学) is commonly shortened to 北大 (lit.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] 'north-great') by also only taking the first character of *Peking*, the "northern capital" (北京; *Beijing*).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In some cases, however, other characters than the first can be selected.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For example, the local short form of 'Hong Kong University' (香港大學) uses *Kong* (港大) rather than *Hong*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Many aspects of academics in Korea follow similar acronym patterns as Chinese, owing to the two languages' commonalities, like using the word for 'big' or 'great' i.e.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] *dae* (대), to refer to universities (대학; *daehak*, literally 'great learning' although 'big school' is an acceptable alternate).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] They can be interpreted similarly to American university appellations, such as "UPenn" or "Texas Tech".
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are shortened forms of the school's name, like how Hongik University (홍익대학교, *Hongik Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Hongdae* (홍대, 'Hong, the big [school]' or 'Hong-U') Other acronyms can refer to the university's main subject, e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Korea National University of Education (한국교원대학교, *Hanguk Gyowon Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Gyowondae* (교원대, 'Big Ed.' or 'Ed.-U').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Other schools use a Koreanized version of their English acronym.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (한국과학기술원, *Hanguk Gwahak Gisulwon*) is referred to as KAIST (카이스트, *Kaiseuteu*) in both English and Korean.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The 3 most prestigious schools in Korea are known as SKY (스카이, *seukai*), combining the first letter of their English names (**S**eoul National, **K**orea, and **Y**onsei Universities).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In addition, the College Scholastic Ability Test (대학수학능력시험, *Daehak Suhang Neungryeok Siheom*) is shortened to *Suneung* (수능, 'S.A.').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The Japanese language makes extensive use of abbreviations, but only some of these are acronyms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Chinese-based words (Sino-Japanese vocabulary) use similar acronym formation to Chinese, like *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō Daigaku* (東京大学, *Tokyo University*).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] It is not always the case that the first character of each word is used, as in Saikyō for 埼京, from *Saitama* + *Tōkyō* (埼玉＋東京), which uses the second character of 東京.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Non-Chinese foreign borrowings (gairaigo) are instead frequently abbreviated as clipped compounds, rather than acronyms, using several initial sounds.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] This is visible in katakana transcriptions of foreign words, but is also found with native words (written in hiragana).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For example, the *Pokémon* media franchise's name originally stood for "pocket monsters" (**ポケ**ット·**モン**スター [po-ke-tto-mon-su-tā] (arrow for r) ポケモン), which is still the long-form of the name in Japanese, or "wāpuro" for "word processor" (**ワー**ド·**プロ**セッサー [wā-do-pu-ro-se-ssā] (arrow for r) ワープロ).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] To a greater degree than English, German often uses syllabic abbreviations instead of acronyms.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some examples are *Gestapo* rather than *GSP* (for *Geheime Staatspolizei*, 'Secret State Police'); *Flak* rather than *FAK* (for *Fliegerabwehrkanone*, 'anti-aircraft gun'); and *Kripo* rather than *KP* (for *Kriminalpolizei*, 'detective division police').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The overuse of such contractions has been mockingly labeled *Aküfi* (for *Abkürzungsfimmel*, 'strange habit of abbreviating').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Examples of *Aküfi* include *Vokuhila* (for *vorne kurz, hinten lang*, 'short in the front, long in the back', i.e., a mullet haircut) and the mocking of Adolf Hitler's title as *Gröfaz* (*Größter Feldherr aller Zeiten*, 'Greatest General of all Time').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Examples (keeping in mind that Hebrew reads right-to-left): ארה״ב (for ארצות הברית, the United States); ברה״מ (for ברית המועצות, the Soviet Union); ראשל״צ (for ראשון לציון, Rishon LeZion); ביה״ס (for בית הספר, the school).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] An example that takes only the initial letters from its component words is צה״ל (*Tzahal*, for צבא הגנה לישראל, Israel Defense Forces).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In inflected forms, the abbreviation sign *gershayim* remains between the second-last and last letters of the non-inflected form of the acronym (e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] 'report', singular: דו״ח, plural: דו״חות; 'squad commander', masculine: מ״כ, feminine: מ״כית).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] There is also a widespread use of acronyms in Indonesia in every aspect of social life.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are considered formal (or officially adopted), while many more are considered informal, slang, or colloquial.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The capital's metropolitan area (Jakarta and its surrounding satellite regions), *Jabodetabek*, is another acronym.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] This stands for *Jakarta-Bogor-Depok-Tangerang-Bekasi*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Many highways are also named by the acronym method, e.g.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] *Jalan Tol* ('Toll Road'), *Jagorawi* (*Jakarta-Bogor-Ciawi*), *Purbaleunyi* (*Purwakarta-Bandung-Cileunyi*), and *Joglo Semar* (*Jogja-Solo-Semarang*).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In some languages, especially those that use certain alphabets, many acronyms come from the governmental use, particularly in the military and law enforcement services.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The Indonesian military (TNI – *Tentara Nasional Indonesia*) and Indonesian police (POLRI – *Kepolisian Republik Indonesia*) are known for heavy acronyms use.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Although not as common as in its sister language Indonesian, a number of Malaysian (*Bahasa Malaysia*) words are formed by merging two words, such as *tadika* from *taman didikan kanak-kanak* ('kindergarten') and *pawagam* from *panggung wayang gambar*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] This, however, has been less prevalent in the modern era, in contrary to Indonesian.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] It is still often for names such as organisation names, among the most famous being MARA from *Majlis Amanah Rakyat* ('People's Trust Council'), a government agency in Malaysia.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Rules in writing initialisms in Malaysian differ based on its script.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In its Latin form, the initialism would be spelt much like in English, using capitals written without any spacing, such as TNB for *Tenaga Nasional Berhad*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In Jawi, however, initialisms differ depending on the source language.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For Malay initialisms, the initial Jawi letters would be written separated by a period such as د.ب.ڤ for ديوان بهاس دان ڤوستاک.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] If the initialism is from a different language, however, it would be written by transliterating each letter from the original language, such as عيم.سي.عيم.سي. for MCMC, or الفا.ڤي.ثيتا for Α.Π.Θ.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Acronyms that use parts of words (not necessarily syllables) are commonplace in Russian as well, e.g. Газпром (*Gazprom*), for Газовая промышленность (*Gazovaya promyshlennost*, 'gas industry').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Most commonly they are pronounced as words, unless they lack vowels, in which case they are pronounced by letters e.g. ФСБ (*ef-es-beh*, 'FSB'), США (*seh-sheh-ah*, USA).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Some foreigh acronyms became own words, such as айти (*IT*) and пиар (*PR*).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Historically, *OTMA* was an acronym sometimes used by the daughters of Emperor Nicholas II of Russia and his consort, Alexandra Feodorovna, as a group nickname for themselves, built from the first letter of each girl's name in the order of their births: Olga, Tatiana, Maria, and Anastasia.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In Swahili, acronyms are common for naming organizations such as *TUKI*, which stands for *Taasisi ya Uchunguzi wa Kiswahili* ('Institute for Swahili Research').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Multiple initial letters (often the initial syllable of words) are often drawn together, as seen more in some languages than others.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In Vietnamese, which has an abundance of compound words, initialisms are very commonly used for both proper and common nouns.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Longer examples include *CHXHCNVN* (*Cộng hòa Xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam*, 'Socialist Republic of Vietnam') and *MTDTGPMNVN* (*Mặt trận Dân tộc Giải phóng miền Nam Việt Nam*, 'Liberation Army of South Vietnam or the National Liberation Front of South Vietnam').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Long initialisms have become widespread in legal contexts in Vietnam, for example *TTLT-VKSNDTC-TANDTC*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] It is also common for a writer to coin an ad hoc initialism for repeated use in an article.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Each letter in an initialism corresponds to one morpheme, that is, one syllable.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] When the first letter of a syllable has a tone mark or other diacritic, the diacritic may be omitted from the initialism, for example *ĐNA* or *ĐNÁ* for *Đông Nam Á* ('Southeast Asia') and *LMCA* or *LMCÂ* for *Liên minh châu Âu* ('European Union').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The letter *Ư* is often replaced by *W* in initialisms to avoid confusion with *U*, for example *UBTWMTTQVN* or *UBTƯMTTQVN* for *Ủy ban Trung ương Mặt trận Tổ quốc Việt Nam* ('Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Initialisms are purely a written convenience, being pronounced the same way as their expansions.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] As the names of many Vietnamese letters are disyllabic, it would be less convenient to pronounce an initialism by its individual letters.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Acronyms pronounced as words are rare in Vietnamese, occurring when an acronym itself is borrowed from another language.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Examples include *SIĐA* (pronounced [s̪i˧ ˀɗaː˧]), a respelling of the French acronym *SIDA* ('AIDS'); *VOA* (pronounced [vwaː˧]), a literal reading of the English initialism for 'Voice of America'; and *NASA* (pronounced [naː˧ zaː˧]), borrowed directly from the English acronym.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] As in Chinese, many compound words can be shortened to the first syllable when forming a longer word.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] For example, the term *Việt Cộng* is derived from the first syllables of *Việt Nam* ('Vietnam') and *Cộng sản* ('communist').
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] This mechanism is limited to Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Unlike with Chinese, such clipped compounds are considered to be portmanteau words or blend words rather than acronyms or initialisms, because the Vietnamese alphabet still requires each component word to be written as more than one character.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In languages where nouns are declined, various methods are used.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] The process above is similar to the way that hyphens are used for clarity in English when prefixes are added to acronyms: thus *pre-NATO policy* (rather than *preNATO*).
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In languages such as Scottish Gaelic and Irish, where lenition (initial consonant mutation) is commonplace, acronyms must also be modified in situations where case and context dictate it.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] In the case of Scottish Gaelic, a lower-case *h* is often added after the initial consonant; for example, 'BBC Scotland' in the genitive case would be written as *BhBC Alba*, with the acronym pronounced *VBC*.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Gaelic acronym for *telebhisean* 'television' is *TBh*, pronounced *TV*, as in English.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] The first press office was founded in the UK in October 1991.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] Media relations were originally handled by the Animal Liberation Front Supporters Group, but a new ALF press office was created to receive claims of responsibility anonymously, in order to avoid charges of conspiracy.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] The name was changed again, this time to the Animal Liberation Press Office, after the introduction of the Terrorism Act 2000, in order to avoid police attention, and to reflect that the office issues statements on behalf of a number of activist groups, not just the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] Robin Webb, formerly a member of the RSPCA ruling council, runs the office in the UK.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] The press office in North America, also known as NAALPO, was co-founded in 1994, and re-opened in December 2004, by Steven Best, an associate professor of philosophy at the University of Texas, El Paso.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] In October 2006, the distinction between the British Animal Liberation Press Office and the ALF was questioned when a High Court judge ruled that Robin Webb was bound by an injunction banning protests at Oxford University.
[src:animal-liberation-press-office/animal-liberation-press-office] Webb had argued that he was a journalist and not a member of the ALF or its supporters group.
